    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_281185">&quot;Bad Fiction&quot; (conclusion)<br />
By Alex &quot;Aura&quot; Sutton<br />
<br />
The look on a mob boss’s face when he thinks he has you by the balls can either be terrifying or amusing. It all depends on whether he’s right or not. After the big shootout, Jackie and I had made our one mistake, and he pounced on it. I have to give him credit; he played his cards well. I guess I could have been pissed that one mistake had landed us in the basement of a building out in God knows where, strapped to chairs, spitting out mouthfuls of blood and teeth onto the floor, but the way I saw it, when you start killing large numbers of people fate isn’t very forgiving.<br />
<br />
Yesterday, when Jackie and I had left the warehouse, we decided we should clean up. Not only were we spattered with blood, but we reeked of death. Here, death means the smell of dried blood, gunpowder, and about fifty men ****ting themselves in the span of fifteen minutes. <br />
<br />
That’s something no one ever tells you. When you die, your body pushes every last bit of waste, bile, and general filth out of you. Every tearful “goodbye” you’ve ever seen in a movie, every time the main character held his beloved in his arms until her eyes closed for the last time, every time a cop used his dying breath to pass the torch on to his rookie, every feat of martyrdom – they all ended with ****ting. Maybe back when we roamed the plains it made the body cleaner to have it all out of you, but the advent of pants kind of put an end to that ideal. It’s not exactly glamorous, but everyone does it, from Gandhi to Superman. The last thing any of us ever does is **** ourselves. If you ask me, it’s proof that God has a sense of humor.<br />
<br />
After it all, Jackie and I decided to go to a hotel, being that my house was just a mound of ash blowing away little by little, and his place was probably already rife with mobsters, and thugs, and other vengeful gun-toting lackeys. We checked into a hotel on the outskirts of town. That was our mistake. We should have run like we meant it. We’d lit the fuse on a powder keg and tried to saunter off looking smug.<br />
<br />
It was midnight when we got to the hotel room. After we showered, neither Jackie nor I slept. <br />
<br />
I tried. I tossed and turned. Jackie didn’t. He just laid in bed, looking up at the ceiling, his old statue- self. Around three in the morning, it hit me.<br />
<br />
It’s easy to get sucked into the action of it all. When you do something crazy like we did, you feel like you’re watching a movie. Explosions, guns, death, survival – it’s some exciting ****. The difference is, when you walk out of a movie you leave it all behind. That doesn’t happen in real life. <br />
<br />
It really sinks in as soon as the movie idealism wears off. You start realizing that your zeal and fervor have real life consequences. It’s easy not to think of them when you start off. Planning revenge when you’re pissed is like going to a restaurant when you’re famished. You don’t look at the prices of anything on the menu. You just order the biggest ******* steak they have. Jackie and my eyes were a bit too big for our bellies and we were both beginning to realize it.<br />
<br />
It’s not like if you’d asked us when we were planning it all, we wouldn’t have been able to put together the words “****” and “fan.” We just didn’t think of it as important. We weren’t expecting to be walking out of that warehouse at all. When you’re planning to end up in a cedar box anyways, you don’t really think about consequences.<br />
<br />
All the possibilities I saw for my future ended up with me getting tortured and killed, and it scared me. It’s funny. A few hours before, I was expecting to get shot in the head and die in the middle of a God forsaken warehouse, and I was surprisingly okay with it. Now, the thought was nauseating, powerfully so. It crept its way up my throat, coating the walls of my esophagus and lining my stomach with sharp, seething dread. My heartbeat grew louder and louder. My breathing became deafening. Soon that’s all I heard. Everything rose in a wild crescendo. I panicked. I rolled off the bed, and made my way to the bathroom as fast as I could. My hands scraped at the floor as I scrambled to the toilet. I threw my head into the bowl. My breaths echoed against the porcelain.<br />
<br />
I heaved a few times. I wanted to put something in the bowl, some part of the bubbling stew of terror and foreboding that was in my stomach right then. Nothing came out. I heaved as hard as I could, but there was nothing.<br />
<br />
Jackie didn’t move. He just stared at the ceiling.<br />
<br />
I tried to vomit for about fifteen minutes before I gave up. I was walking back through the doorway to the bathroom when the door to the hotel room flew off its hinges. Ten or fifteen armed men burst in. I lunged for my gun, but they were quicker than me. They clipped me on the back of the head with something cold and hard. The last thing I saw before I hit the ground was Jackie, calm and cool. He didn’t even stand up to fight them. He knew this was an eventuality and didn’t seem too eager to try and fight fate.<br />
<br />
--------------------------------------------------<br />
<br />
When I came to, they were already beating the hell out of me. Even if you’ve never been in a fight, you have a pretty good idea what it’s supposed to feel like and sound like when someone punches you in the face. You know the pain should be dull, but heavy. You know the sound should be a muted “Thud!”<br />
<br />
I could barely see, but a muscular grunt told me another fist was coming toward my face. There wasn’t a thud, there wasn’t even a crack. Just a wet smacking sound and no pain. I couldn’t feel a God damned thing on my face. I wanted to feel pain. I wanted to hurt, something to tell me that it all wasn’t as bad as I knew it to be, but there wasn’t - just a terrible lack of agony telling me they were doing little more than pounding warm hamburger meat.<br />
<br />
One more grunt. Another splish. The chair I was tied to toppled back over and my head hit the pavement with a “crack.” Pain rushed outward across my body, and my entire consciousness paused for a moment. At least I could still feel something. I groaned a little, and they realized I was awake. I felt them sit the chair up. Someone toweled the blood out of my eyes, and the room came into focus around me. From the looks of it, there had been about five guys taking turns on me. They had swapped out when their hands got too ****** up from the protruding bones in my face to keep punching. I coughed out a chuckle – you’ve gotta take your victories where you can.<br />
<br />
I looked to my right, there was Jackie. His pulverized face was still somehow stoic. He was never great at showing emotion. I’d seen him smile only one time, the night at the Maidenhead when we’d first met. He told me once that he was a cheery guy before his family died. At first, I didn’t believe him – but when I looked harder at his face, I could see it. I always found it amazing to think that there are some people who believe that the stresses and tribulations we go through in every day life get expressed in nothing but our demeanors. There’s a reason that the first reaction you usually have to a person’s face is usually the correct one. People get the faces they deserve. Life etches its story into the bags under your eyes, the wrinkles in your cheeks, and the color of your hair. An angry man’s brow grows its way down, hardening into an ever present scowl. A bitter woman’s lips purse up, and her eyes shrink and she’ll forever look like she’s trying to hold a quarter between her ass cheeks. <br />
<br />
A broken man’s face is like a mansion whose caretakers have left it behind. Its unsightliness – hanging vines, overgrown gardens, and shattered windows – is somehow inviting. You want to explore it, maybe a little out of morbid curiosity, but there’s something else there driving you. Part of you wants to explore so maybe you can see some of the luster that once was. You want to be able to imagine the house as it once stood. You might even fantasize about how you’re going to fix it up someday and make it a home again, but you never will. That was Jackie’s face – broken, beaten, dirty, ugly… but friendly in spite of it all.<br />
<br />
When I had asked him why he smiled the night he met me, he said that he knew I was a herald. He knew who I was and where I’d been as soon as I walked into the bar that night, and he knew that night was a beginning. It’s easy to smile when you realize that you’re beginning the story of your life, and that’s what Jackie thought this whole thing was. Back when we were planning the warehouse, I asked Jackie if he thought we would succeed, and he told me, “Of course we will. This is our story, not theirs. Main characters don’t die until they do what they’ve got to.” Jackie’s eccentricity was always strangely comforting.<br />
<br />
Even now, beaten and bloody, so weak he could barely swing his head to the side and look at me, Jackie looked confident – like a poker player who’s sitting on a straight flush when everyone’s counted him out of the game.<br />
<br />
Jackie and I both rolled our heads forward as the door to the room swung open and an all-too-familiar fat man waddled his way in. My body mustered what little strength it had and tried to throw itself out of the chair at him. That effort culminated in a weak twitching of my arms and legs. The fat son of a bitch only laughed.<br />
<br />
“You know the Chinks won’t buy heroin from me anymore?” he said as he waved a pistol in front of my face. His accusatory tone led me to believe we were the cause. I had wondered what was in those crates at the warehouse.<br />
<br />
“Ya don’t say?” I said. Trying to articulate the words was like trying to perfectly pry apart the two halves of a peanut butter sandwich. The phrase came out in a strained, soppy mess. Blood fell out of my mouth as I spoke and splattered on the floor beneath me.<br />
<br />
“I’m impressed,” he mocked, “you can still talk. I guess my men didn’t do their job.” He pistol-whipped me across the jaw. The joke was on him. I still couldn’t feel that part of my face. I smiled just to piss him off.<br />
<br />
“I bet you thought you were being real heroic back there. You were gonna show us good, weren’t ya? Have me sitting in my office shaking in my boots? You were gonna be just like in the movies. Well look where ya ended up. No cameras here. I don’t think Buck Rogers ever got himself in a mess like this… Of course, he’s dead – and you’re gonna be soon, so I guess the two of you do share that in common.” He was just speaking to hear himself talk. Gloating in his victory for his sake, not ours.<br />
<br />
The look on a mob boss’s face when he thinks he has you by the balls can either be terrifying or amusing. Jackie made his feelings clear. He started laughing. Before then, I didn’t think he was capable. He’d always been the grizzly statue I’d met at the bar that night, laughter and him seemed as out of place as somersaulting in a funeral procession. I turned to look at him, and I saw what he was laughing about.<br />
<br />
I’ll never know how he did it. I guess the guards didn’t search him when they brought him in, but clasped in his hands tied behind his back was an unmistakably green hunk of metal. Laying on the ground below was a silver pin, glinting brilliantly against the pallid gray of the basement’s concrete floor. The last thing I saw was Jackie grinning ear to ear. It’s easy to smile at the beginning of your story. I guess it’s easy to smile at the end of the story, too.<br />
<br />
--------------------------------------------------<br />
<br />
The explosion from a grenade is a funny thing. It’s nothing like you see in the movies. Movie grenades make a loud, destructive, fiery “Ka-boom.” In real life, it’s actually quite peaceful. You don’t even hear the full explosion. All you hear is the “Ka-.” Either you’re dead or you’ve gone deaf from the intensity of the noise. I can’t tell you what happens in the former case, but in the latter the next thing you see is a taupe colored ceiling. You’re like a stone skipping across the surface of time. The movies do help with one thing. Thanks to them, you can pretty quickly identify the redundant “click-hiss” of a respirator and the steady beeping of a heart monitor.<br />
<br />
Some people say it’s disorienting waking up in a hospital bed. I just found it God damned irritating. That’d have been such a fitting end to me – dead in the process of bringing down the son of a bitch who took away my family. Unfortunately, God decided I should keep on living. I wondered if he was doing it out of sadism, or just ignorant sympathy.<br />
<br />
They told me I’d been in a coma for three months. They had taken the liberty of reconstructing my face while I’d been out. Plastic surgery can do a lot, but it really takes something away. Sure, I look in the mirror and I see a face staring back at me, but it’s not me. The first time I saw it, I thought of Jackie. I thought of his face, and the volumes it spoke. Mine didn’t say anything, now. It was alive with all the history of a wicker chair you bought at Cracker Barrel, just a bland souvenir constructed unlovingly by some clown who’s a tradesman, not an artist. It had no character, no personality, no history. It was just a skull wrapped in skin.<br />
<br />
Every story my face would have told had been wiped clean with the stroke of a surgeon’s knife. I guess it was for the best anyway. Jackie was right about himself. He was the main character. He accomplished what he needed to and made his exit gracefully. I was just a supporting character in the whole ordeal. Sure I contributed to everything, but the story ended with Jackie. The rest of my life to this point has been inconsequential and unsightly. I spend most nights sitting alone at the corner of the bar in the Maidenhead, drowning my sorrows in scotch and surviving off of the insurance money from the house and my dead family, waiting for my story to begin.</div>
